Farkle is a dice game of chance and strategy played with six dice and two or more players. The objective is to be the first player to reach or exceed 10,000 points.

Basic Gameplay Rules
- Each player takes turns rolling all six dice at once.
- After each roll, the player must set aside at least one scoring die or combination of dice.
- The player can then either end their turn and bank the points accumulated during that turn or continue rolling the remaining dice to try to increase their score.
- If the player scores with all six dice in a turn (called "hot dice"), they may roll all six dice again and continue accumulating points.
- If a roll results in no scoring dice ("farkle"), the player loses all points accumulated during that turn, and the turn passes to the next player.
- The game continues with players accumulating points over multiple turns until one player reaches or exceeds 10,000 points.
- After a player reaches 10,000 points, other players have one last turn to try to surpass that score.

Scoring
- Single 1s are worth 100 points.
- Single 5s are worth 50 points.
- Three of a kind (numbers 2-6) score 100 times the number (e.g., three 4s = 400 points).
- Three 1s score 1,000 points.
- 4 of a Kind – 1000 points.
- 5 of a Kind – 2000 points.
- 6 of a Kind – 3000 points.
- A straight (1-6) scores 1,500 points.
- Three pairs score 1,500 points.
- Four of a kind plus a pair scores 1,500 points.
- Two sets of three of a kind score 2,500 points.

Players must score points from dice in the current roll only; dice from previous rolls in the same turn cannot be combined to form new scoring combinations.

This summary covers the most common and official rules, but many house rules and scoring variations exist across different groups and regions.